{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nThe original premise (promote a bash credential helper, wire a dispatcher arm, add `.rebar/config.conf` + `read-config.sh`) is OBSOLETE after the bash->Python migration. Config PERSISTENCE + reconciler-READ are already solved: `resolve_jira_settings` (`src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/acli_subprocess.py`) resolves url/user/project through `load_config().jira.*` (typed `JiraConfig`, reading `rebar.toml [tool.rebar.jira]` and legacy `.rebar/config.conf`), with `JIRA_URL/USER/PROJECT` env overriding and `JIRA_API_TOKEN` env-only; `rebar bridge-probe` already validates credentials end-to-end. The ONLY genuinely-missing piece is an INTERACTIVE onboarding UX.\n\n## What\nAdd an interactive `rebar jira-onboard` subcommand (intercept, like `rebar llm`/`reconcile`; owns its own `--help`) that detects existing Jira settings via `resolve_jira_settings`, prompts for missing url/user/project, persists them to the EXISTING typed config, guides on the env-only token, and runs `bridge-probe` validation. Mirror the `rebar llm setup` wizard precedent (`src/rebar/_cli/_llm_commands.py`). New impl file `src/rebar/_cli/_jira_onboard.py`.\n\n## Scope\n- New `rebar jira-onboard` CLI intercept (Python). Detect via `resolve_jira_settings()` (so detection reflects env-over-file precedence + the env-only token). Prompt for missing url/user/project. Non-interactive flags `--url/--user/--project` and `--no-validate`; `--reset` clears the persisted `[tool.rebar.jira]` section.\n- Persist url/user/project via a NEW minimal config writer in `src/rebar/config.py` (`write_jira_config(...)`). The token is NEVER written.\n- Reuse `bridge-probe` as the post-onboard end-to-end check.\n- Out: any new config LAYER (read path), persisting secrets to disk, touching the reconciler read path (already done).\n\n## Mechanism — config write (resolves BLOCK #1, T1/T3/T9/E1/E2)\n- Add `write_jira_config(url, user, project, *, root=None) -> Path` to `config.py`. NO new dependency: hand-rolled, format-aware, atomic (write tmp + `os.replace`).\n- **Deterministic target-selection rule** (so a tester knows which file to inspect): use `_discover_project_config(root)`. If it returns a `toml` (`rebar.toml`) or `pyproject` file, surgically UPSERT the `[tool.rebar.jira]` / `[jira]` table in place, PRESERVING all other content (parse with tomllib to know existing keys, then replace/insert only the jira section's three keys via text-region splice). If it returns a `legacy` `.rebar/config.conf`, upsert dotted `jira.url/user/project=` lines. If NONE is discovered, CREATE `rebar.toml` at the repo root with a `[jira]` table.\n- Only the three non-secret keys are ever written; `api_token` is never a key. Atomic temp-file replace prevents partial/corrupt files on interruption.\n\n## Mechanism — validation env bridge (resolves BLOCK #2, T3)\n- `bridge-probe` (`jira-capability-probe.py`) reads `JIRA_URL/USER/PROJECT/API_TOKEN` from `os.environ` directly. After persisting to a file, those values are NOT in the subprocess env. The wizard therefore re-resolves via `resolve_jira_settings()` and injects the resolved url/user/project into the child env before invoking the probe, and requires `JIRA_API_TOKEN` to be present in the env (else it skips the live probe with a clear \"export JIRA_API_TOKEN then run `rebar bridge-probe`\" message). This closes the file->env gap so validation reflects what was just persisted.\n\n## Failure / edge paths (resolves T6/E5)\n- Empty input at a required prompt re-prompts; EOF/Ctrl-C aborts cleanly (exit 1, no partial write). A failing bridge-probe surfaces its PROBE_FAIL and returns non-zero but the persisted config is kept (config write and validation are separate steps). Config-write OSError is reported and returns non-zero. `--no-validate` skips the probe. Token absent at validation time => guidance, not a hard probe failure.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `rebar jira-onboard` interactive subcommand: detects existing settings (via `resolve_jira_settings`), prompts for missing url/user/project, persists them to the existing typed config, and runs `bridge-probe` validation (with the resolved settings injected into the probe env).\n- [ ] Persistence uses the deterministic target rule above (discovered rebar.toml/pyproject `[tool.rebar.jira]` upsert; legacy `.rebar/config.conf` dotted keys; else create `rebar.toml`), is atomic, and preserves other config content.\n- [ ] `JIRA_API_TOKEN` is treated as an env-only secret (guidance shown; NEVER written to any config file); reuses `resolve_jira_settings`/`load_config().jira` (no new config layer).\n- [ ] Non-interactive (`--url/--user/--project`, `--no-validate`), `--reset`, and `--help` paths supported; EOF/empty-input handled.\n- [ ] Documented (CLI `--help` text + a docs mention where Jira setup is documented).\n- [ ] Tests cover: detect existing vs missing; persist writes url/user/project to the config file (toml upsert preserving other keys, legacy conf, and create-new); the env-only-token rule (token NEVER written); `--reset`. Full suite green.\n\n## Files\n- `src/rebar/_cli/_jira_onboard.py` (new; wizard impl + entry point `_jira_onboard`)\n- `src/rebar/_cli/__init__.py` (intercept wiring)\n- `src/rebar/config.py` (new `write_jira_config` writer)\n- `docs/` Jira-setup mention\n- `tests/unit/test_jira_onboard.py` (new)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782781381524506001,"uuid":"cefafb93-4b71-433e-afdf-8f1e7f722b84"}